A cursor in SQL is a database object used to retrieve and process rows one at a time from a result set.

## Why Cursors Are Used
SQL is designed for set-based operations (working on all rows together), but sometimes you need row-by-row logic, such as:
>Applying complex calculations per row
>Performing conditional updates
>Iterating through records sequentially
```
DECLARE emp_cursor CURSOR FOR
SELECT Name FROM Employees;

OPEN emp_cursor;

FETCH NEXT FROM emp_cursor INTO @name;

WHILE @@FETCH_STATUS = 0
BEGIN
    PRINT @name;
    FETCH NEXT FROM emp_cursor INTO @name;
END;

CLOSE emp_cursor;
DEALLOCATE emp_cursor;
```

## Definition
A **decorator** is a function that wraps another function to extend its behaviour without modifying it directly.

## Example
```
def my_decorator(func):
    def wrapper():
        print("Before")
        func()
        print("After")
    return wrapper

@my_decorator
def say_hello():
    print("Hello!")
```
Calling `say_hello()` prints: Before → Hello! → After
